The '''1998 [[Lignes Aériennes Congolaises (1997-2003)|Lignes Aériennes Congolaises]] crash''' refers to a non-scheduled domestic [[Kindu]]–[[Kinshasa]] passenger service that was shot down by rebel forces, just after [[takeoff]] from [[Kindu Airport]], during climbout, on 10 October 1998.<ref name="ASN"/> All 41 occupants of the aircraft perished in the incident.<ref name="ASN"/>

==Aircraft==
The aircraft involved was a [[Lignes Aériennes Congolaises (1997-2003)|Lignes Aériennes Congolaises]] [[Boeing 727-30]], [[Aircraft registration|registration]] 9Q-CSG, that had its maiden flight on 10 March 1965.<ref name="ASN"/><ref name="FI"/> The airframe was {{Age|1965|3|10|1998|10|10}} years old at the time of the crash.

==Description of the event==
The [[Lignes Aériennes Congolaises (1997-2003)|Lignes Aériennes Congolaises]] [[Boeing 727-30]] took off from [[Kindu]] Airport (KND/FZOA) on a domestic non-scheduled passenger flight to [[N'djili Airport]] in [[Kinshasa]] with 38 passengers and 3 crew on board. Only 3 minutes into the flight, the rear of the aircraft was struck by a Russian-made shoulder-fired [[Strela 2]] [[surface-to-air missile]]. The captain attempted an emergency landing, but the 727 crashed into a dense [[jungle]] near [[Kindu]]. All 41 people on board perished.<ref name="ASN"/>

