{{Infobox military conflict| conflict=Battle of Shimbra Kure |partof=the [[Abyssinian–Adal war]] |image= |caption= |date=March, 1529 |place=[[Shimbra Kure]], [[Ethiopia]], {{convert|80|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} southeast of [[Addis Ababa]] |result= Decisive [[Adal Sultanate|Adal]] victory |combatant1=[[File:Flag_of_Adal.png|22px]] [[Adal Sultanate]] |combatant2=[[File:Ethiopian_Pennants.svg|22px]] [[Ethiopian Empire]] |commander1=[[Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi|Imam Ahmad Gragn]] |commander2=[[Dawit II of Ethiopia|Dawit II]] |strength1=12600 men several thousand infantry, cavalry |strength2=200000 man of infantry and cavalry |casualties1= |casualties2= }} {{Campaignbox Abyssinian–Adal war}}
The '''Battle of Shimbra Kure''' ("[[chickpea]] swamp") was fought in March 1529 between the forces of [[Adal Sultanate|Adal]] led by [[Imam]] [[Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi]], and the [[Ethiopian Empire|Ethiopian]] army, under [[Dawit II of Ethiopia|Dawit II]] (Lebna Dengel). The army of Imam Ahmad prevailed, and were in control of the field at the end of the battle. Both sides suffered heavy casualties.<ref>Richard Pankhurst, ''The Ethiopian Borderlands'' (Lawrenceville: Red Sea Press, 1997), p. 172</ref> Despite this success, and his desire to capture and hold the Emperor's palace at [[Badeqe]], Imam Ahmad, in part to appease his restive men, withdrew from the highlands and did not return to directly engage the Ethiopian army for two years.<ref>Sihab ad-Din Ahmad bin 'Abd al-Qader, ''Futuh al-Habasa: The conquest of Ethiopia'', translated by Paul Lester Stenhouse with annotations by Richard Pankhurst (Hollywood: Tsehai, 2003),p. 86</ref>
Some authorities, such as [[Richard Pankhurst (academic)|Richard Pankhurst]], attribute Imam Ahmad's success to the presence amongst his followers of an elite company of [[matchlock]]men. If this is the case, then this battle was the first time Ethiopian forces had to fight against a force armed with firearms.<ref>Pankhurst, ''Borderlands'', p. 168</ref>
