The '''Dawada''' (Duwwud, Dawwada) is an [[Afro-Arab]] ethnic group from the [[Fezzan]] region of southern [[Libya]]. They live around the Gabraoun oasis, at the town of [[Murzuk]], where they harvest [[brine shrimp]] in the salty lakes. They dry the brine shrimp and sell them to caravans. The name Dawada means "worm-folk" in [[Arabic language|Arabic]] due to this practice. The appearance of the Dawada is distinctive and has been likened to the [[Khoisan]], perhaps a [[relict]] population. They are mostly an [[Endogamy|endogamic]] group which rarely marry outside of their tribe. They speak an [[Arabic language|Arabic]] dialect.<ref name=civ>{{cite book|last1=Fernandez-Armesto|first1=Felipe|title=Civilizations: Culture, Ambition, and the Transformation of Nature|date=2001|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9780743216500|pages=560|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3MNzi698aXwC&pg=PA65&dq=Dawada++Fezzan&hl=en&sa=X&ei=r2DAVILNHdCUsQSOp4DQDg&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Dawada%20%20Fezzan&f=false|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref>


