'''Ganwa''' is the name for the [[princely]] group that traditionally ruled [[Burundi]]. Some say that they formed a distinct ethnic group.<ref>[http://www.burundivoices.org/eng/background02.asp Ethnic Conflict in Burundi]</ref> Others say that they were generally part of the wider [[Tutsi]] ethnicity.<ref>[https://books.google.be/books?id=nrN077AEgzMC&pg=PA205&lpg=PA205&dq=Ganwa+ethnic&source=bl&ots=LWxFz3l518&sig=Kx_rXiaYKZmcmQKwjIQJrZg6rSQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_-tdVZioOsyZsgGFxoEQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Ganwa%20ethnic&f=false Civil Wars of the World: Major Conflicts Since World War II, Volume 1] page 205</ref> Whatever the case may be, they have themselves launched several appeals to be recognized as a distinct socio-cultural grouping.<ref>[http://theafricanresource.com/country-profiles/east-africa/burundi/ Identity, politics, and economics in the East African Community’s most troubled member]</ref>

