{{Politics of Comoros}}
'''Realising Freedom's Capability''', also known as '''Uwezo''' (''Leadership''), was a political party in the [[Comoros]].
==History== The party was established in [[Paris]] by former Foreign Minister [[Abdallah Mouazoir]] in 1984 as the '''Union for a Democratic Republic in the Comoros''' (''Union pour une République Démocratique aux Comores'', URDC).<ref name=HD>Martin Ottenheimer & Harriet Ottenheimer (1994) ''Historical Dictionary of the Comoro Islands'', Scarecrow Press, p86</ref> In 1990 it was reorganised as UWEZO.<ref name=HD/> The party was part of the "no" camp for the [[Comorian constitutional referendum, 1992|1992 constitutional referendum]].<ref>[http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:WR8Skg6uIBMJ:www.africaintelligence.fr/ION/politics/1992/05/30/referendum-eve-confusion,15160-ART+&cd=4&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=uk Comoros Islands: Referendum-eve confusion] African Intelligence, 30 May 1992</ref> It won a single seat in the [[Comorian legislative election, 1992|1992 elections]],<ref>[http://www.africaintelligence.com/ION/politics/1992/12/26/unlucky-for-some%2C17969-ART?CXT=CANP&country=COMOROS%20ISLANDS Comoros Islands: Unlucky for some] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130041209/https://www.africaintelligence.com/ION/politics/1992/12/26/unlucky-for-some%2C17969-ART?CXT=CANP&country=COMOROS%20ISLANDS |date=2016-11-30 }} African Intelligence, 26 December 1992</ref> and retained it in [[Comorian legislative election, 1993|early elections]] the following year.
The party nominated Mouazoir as its candidate for the [[Comorian presidential election, 1996|1996 presidential elections]]. Abdallah failed to make the second round. Later in 1996 it was one of several parties that merged to form the [[National Rally for Development]].<ref>[http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:V9SGTS8gq6wJ:www.africaintelligence.fr/ION/politics/1996/10/12/constitutional-referendum,39722-ART+&cd=9&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=uk Comoros Islands: Constitutional referendum] African Intelligence, 12 October 1996</ref>
